Hedging</A></P>=0A  <P><A HREF=3D\"FX1.html#Tr=\nading\">Case Studies - Trading</A></P>=0A  <P><A HREF=3D\"FX1.html#Investment=\n\">Case Studies - Investments</A></P>=0A  <P><A HREF=3D\"FX1.html#Summary\">Su=\nmmary</A></P>=0A </BLOCKQUOTE>=0A</TD></TR>=0A</TABLE>=0A=0A=0A<A NAME=3D\"I=\nntro\"></a><p>=0A=0A<hr>=0A<H2><CENTER>Introduction</CENTER></H2>=0A=0A<P>Th=\ne currency turmoil seen in recent years, together with increasingly=0Agloba=\nl and competitive markets, have added to the difficulties faced by=0Athe co=\nrporate hedger and institutional investor in managing foreign exchange=0Ari=\nsk. With multinational companies exposed through offshore plants and/or=0Ao=\nverseas sourcing and sales, and investors exposed to currency risk through=\n=0Across border investments, demand for effective risk management instrumen=\nts=0Ahas grown dramatically.</P>=0A=0A<P>Companies and institutions have fo=\nund that currency options offer them=0Apossibilities to capitalise on favou=\nrable exchange rate movements while=0Aproviding protection from adverse mov=\nements. With competitors equally able=0Ato neutralise risk without sacrific=\ning the opportunities to be found in=0Afavourable markets, today's risk man=\nagers are finding that the advantages=0Aof currency options cannot be ignor=\ned.</P>=0A=0A<P>Risk managers who hedge with options range from the simples=\nt one person=0Atreasury to the &#147;ultra-sophisticated&#148; profit orien=\ntated trading=0Aroom. All realise that the foreign exchange market can be t=\noo volatile to=0Aremain exposed, and yet business may be too competitive to=\n sacrifice opportunity.</P>=0A=0A<P>Genesis&#146;s Foreign Exchange Options=\n Group responds to this need. A=0Aworld-class provider of risk management e=\nxpertise, Genesis holds a prominent=0Aposition in the global foreign exchan=\nge markets.</P>=0A=0A<P>Our worldwide network includes principal trading de=\nsks in Asia, the US=0Aand Europe, putting us at the forefront of foreign ex=\nchange markets 24 hours=0Aa day. Genesis provides foreign exchange services=\n to a broad range of customers=0Aand trades virtually all currencies.</P>=\n=0A=0A<P>In the currency options markets, Genesis is a recognised leader. W=\ne design=0Aoption strategies and products to meet clients&#146; individual =\nneeds, giving=0Aflexibility and competitive pricing, and ensuring that clie=\nnts receive the=0Alevel of hedging they require. Our aim is to be the world=\n&#146;s number=0Aone risk management provider.</P>=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#Top\"=\n>...Back to contents</A>=0A=0A<A NAME=3D\"Options\"></a><p>=0A=0A<hr>=0A=0A=\n=0A<H2><CENTER>Foreign Exchange Options Expertise</CENTER></H2>=0A=0A<P>Gen=\nesis&#146;s Foreign Exchange Options Group ranks=0Ain the top tier among OT=\nC (over-the-counter) and exchange traded FX option=0Amarket-makers, trading=\n options in all the major currencies and most of the=0Aliquid exotic curren=\ncies. Genesis&#146;s presence in the major trading centres=0Ain the US, Eur=\nope and Asia allows us to provide a 24-hour service to our=0Aglobal client =\nbase. These resources, plus Genesis&#146;s investment in the=0Aoption produ=\nct, enable us to provide excellent pricing and risk management=0Aservice ac=\nross a diverse range of currencies and products for our clients.</P>=0A=0A<=\nH3>Flexibility</H3>=0A=0A<P>The key advantage of using options for hedging,=\n trading or investment=0Apurposes, is the flexibility they provide. Options=\n allow their users to=0Aput a value on risk, an important aid in the proces=\ns of making decisions=0Aon risk portfolio management.</P>=0A=0A<P>Flexibili=\nty is also a feature of the service provided by Genesis, both=0Ain terms of=\n currency pairs available and option maturities. Portfolios in=0Aexcess of =\n70 currency pairs are traded by Genesis&#146;s Foreign Exchange=0AOptions G=\nroup, for maturities ranging from a single day to over 10 years=0A(forward =\nmarkets permitting). New and innovative exotic options products=0Aare const=\nantly being developed, enabling Genesis to tailor option solutions=0Ato ind=\nividual business or investment needs.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Understanding Risk</H3>=\n=0A=0A<P>The basic principle of an option is a simple one. The holder has t=\nhe=0Aright (but not the obligation) to transact and the writer has an oblig=\nation=0Ato transact should the holder wish to exercise its right. More comp=\nlex option=0Acombinations and exotic options are based on these fundamental=\n principles,=0Aand Genesis invests much time and effort in helping clients =\nunderstand how=0Aoptions could address their needs in the risk management o=\nf their currency=0Aportfolio. The risk/reward implications of different opt=\nion strategies are=0Aclearly explained to clients so that they can decide w=\nhich is the most appropriate=0Astrategy for their purposes. Genesis&#146;s =\nForeign Exchange Options Group=0Ahas expanded its internal training program=\nmes for FX marketing executives=0Ato ensure that clients aims and exposures=\n can be best understood and serviced.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Solutions</H3>=0A=0A<P>I=\nn today&#146;s environment, individual risk appetites, market views=0Aand h=\nedging objectives differ greatly. At the same time, there is a vast=0Aarray=\n of option structures and exotic option products available which could=0Abe=\n applied to risk portfolios. In order for options to be integrated effectiv=\nely=0Ainto a customer&#146;s FX strategy, Genesis&#146;s Foreign Exchange O=\nptions=0AGroup works with each one to suggest appropriate structures, in ke=\neping=0Awith the client&#146;s expectations, cost and risk mitigation prior=\nities.=0AAfter consideration of the alternatives, the option solution most =\nappropriate=0Ato the specific set of objectives, appetites and views can be=\n selected by=0Athe customer.</P>=0A=0A<P>Genesis&#146;s service extends bey=\nond inception of the deal, helping customers=0Aadjust their hedge positions=\n in the light of changing market conditions.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Emerging Market C=\nurrencies</H3>=0A=0A<P>As the global markets expand, so does the demand for=\n hedging tools in=0Athe more exotic currencies, and Genesis spares no effor=\nt to provide versatile=0Asolutions for clients with exposure in the less li=\nquid markets. As one of=0Athe most active market makers in exotic currency =\nspot and forward markets,=0Awe are well placed to achieve effective option =\nhedges, where possible, for=0Athose clients investing in or trading with th=\ne relevant countries.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Summary</H3>=0A=0A<P>Genesis provides a =\nwide range of foreign exchange option services in its=0Apartnership with it=\ns clients: flexibility both in maturities and currency=0Apairs quoted; know=\nledgeable and focused assistance in defining and analysing=0Arisk; and inno=\nvative solutions designed to fit clients&#146; individual=0Asituations.</P>=\n=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#Top\">...Back to contents</A>=0A=0A<A NAME=3D\"What\"></a=\n><p>=0A=0A<hr>=0A=0A<H2><CENTER>What are Foreign Exchange Options?</CENTER>=\n</H2>=0A=0A<P>A standard option gives the holder the right, but not the obl=\nigation,=0Ato buy a specified amount of one currency for another at a speci=\nfic rate=0Aon or before a specific date. The buyer of the option pays an up=\n front premium=0Afor that right. </P>=0A=0A<P>A Call allows the holder to b=\nuy the currency, whereas a Put allows the=0Aholder to sell the currency. In=\n the foreign exchange markets though, as=0Aevery transaction involves the p=\nurchase of one currency and the sale of=0Aanother, a Call on one currency w=\nill by definition be a Put on the other=0Acurrency of the pair. If the hold=\ner of the option decides to take up the=0Aright to buy (sell) the currency =\nspecified in the option, he is said to=0Aexercise the option and the option=\n contract becomes a simple FX contract.=0AThe holder of the option willingl=\ny exercises when the market is favourable=0Afor him to do so, otherwise he =\nwill allow the option to lapse and expire=0Aworthless.</P>=0A=0A<P>The curr=\nency options market began as an exchange-traded market: in December=0A1982,=\n the Philadelphia Stock Exchange launched its first FX options contract=0Ao=\nn sterling against the US dollar. Since then, the OTC market - options=0Atr=\naded between counterparties - has grown to be much larger than the exchange=\n-traded=0Amarket. Currency options are now actively traded in a wide range =\nof currency=0Apairs across a diversity of maturities.</P>=0A=0A<P>The princ=\nipal difference between exchange-traded options and OTC options=0Ais that t=\nhe former are typically available in a limited number of currencies,=0Astri=\nke prices, and maturities; OTC options, because they are subject to=0Anegot=\niations between buyer and seller, can include any mutually agreed terms.=0A=\nExchange-traded options carry very little risk of counterparty default,=0Aw=\nhile OTC options are executed on the basis of lines of credit to the counte=\nrparty.</P>=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#Top\">...Back to contents</A>=0A=0A=0A<A NAM=\nE=3D\"Pricing\"></a><p>=0A=0A<hr>=0A<H2><CENTER>Pricing Options</CENTER></H2>=\n=0A=0A<P>The holder of an option has the right but not the obligation to=0A=\nexecute a specific FX transaction in the future. The ultimate value of that=\n=0Aright depends on where the spot market is trading in the future. </P>=0A=\n=0A<P>Since the future is unknown, one must make an educated guess about wh=\nere=0Athe spot market might be in order to determine the value of that righ=\nt today.=0AThis is what option pricing theory is all about. Rather than try=\ning to predict=0Athe future spot rate, however, option pricing takes a syst=\nematic, mathematical=0Aapproach to the educated guess.</P>=0A=0A<P>The calc=\nulation relies heavily on probability theory. The principal concepts=0Aare =\nexpected value and the lognormal distribution.</P>=0A=0A<P>Expected value (=\nE.V.) is the payoff of an event multiplied by the probability=0Aof it occur=\nring. For example, the probability of rolling a six on one die=0Ais 1/6, or=\n 16.67%. The E.V. of a game in which one is paid $100 for rolling=0Aa six a=\nnd nothing for any other roll is</P>=0A=0A<DIR>=0A  <P><blockquote>=0A  <P>=\n(1/6 x $100) + (5/6 x $0) =3D $16.67=0A  <P></blockquote>=0A</DIR>=0A=0A<P>=\nThe expected value is the fair price for playing such a game.</P>=0A=0A<P>A=\nn option&#146;s premium can be thought of in the same way, although=0Ainste=\nad of six possible outcomes, there are hundreds: all the spot rates=0Athat =\nmight prevail at the option&#146;s expiration. Each outcome will have=0Aspe=\ncific value. This will be either zero, if the option is out-of-the-money=0A=\nat expiry, or the difference between the closing spot and the strike price=\n=0Aif the option is in-the-money. Each closing spot rate can also be thought=\n=0Aof as having its own probability. If, for each outcome, one multiplied t=\nhe=0Avalue of that outcome by its probability, and then added up the result=\ns,=0Athe sum would be the premium of the option.</P>=0A=0A<P>The expected v=\nalue of an option, the probability-weighted sum of all=0Aits possible payof=\nfs, is its fair price.</P>=0A=0A<P>The probabilities associated with rollin=\ng one die are easy to calculate.=0ATo calculate the probabilities associate=\nd with spot rates occurring some=0Atime in the future, option pricing model=\ns use a lognormal distribution curve.</P>=0A=0A<P>A lognormal distribution =\ndescribes the likelihood that the market will=0Avary from current levels by=\n the end of a given time period. It operates=0Aunder two critical assumptio=\nns:</P>=0A=0A<BLOCKQUOTE>=0A  <P><STRONG>a)</STRONG> that the market moves =\nin a <I><STRONG>random walk</STRONG></I>=0A  - a move up by 1% has the same=\n probability as a move down by the same degree;</P>=0A  <P><STRONG>b)</STRO=\nNG> that the mean of the distribution, and therefore=0A  the most probable =\nmarket price at the end of the period, is today&#146;s=0A  current market r=\nate. In foreign exchange options, that means the <I><STRONG>forward=0A  out=\nright rate</STRONG></I> associated with the time period.</P>=0A</BLOCKQUOTE>=\n=0A=0A<P>Other things being equal, a large distribution will result in a la=\nrge=0Aoption price. This is because it will encompass large positive return=\ns (extremely=0Ain-the-money outcomes); these are not offset by equally larg=\ne negative returns,=0Asince an option cannot be worth less than zero. A sma=\nll distribution will=0Agenerate a low option value because only modest posi=\ntive returns fall within=0Athe realms of probability.</P>=0A=0A<P>What then=\n determines the size of a distribution curve? Market prices=0Acannot move u=\nnless there is <B><I>time</I></B> in which to travel; nor can=0Athey move u=\nnless there is some degree of motion in rates, or <B><I>volatility</I></B>.=\n=0AIt is in defining the likely range of future spot prices and their relat=\nive=0Aprobabilities, that time and volatility play their essential role in =\noption=0Apricing.</P>=0A=0A<P>The distribution curve applicable to a given =\noption is constantly changing.=0ATime inexorably passes, which inevitably s=\nhrinks the range around current=0Alevels that the market might exhibit at e=\nxpiry (this is how <B><I>time decay</I></B>=0Aaffects an option price). In =\naddition, the volatility component of the calculation=0Ais constantly chang=\ning &#151; this is an estimate made by option traders=0Aabout future behavi=\nour of the spot market &nbsp;&#151; and effectively when=0Athey buy and sel=\nl options they are &#145;trading volatility&#146;. An option=0Apremium is a=\nlso affected by the <B><I>location</I></B> of the distribution=0Acurve rela=\ntive to the option&#146;s strike price.</P>=0A=0A<P>For an option where the=\n forward outright is equal to the strike price=0A(at-the-money), half of th=\ne possible outcomes will be positive and half=0Awill be zero (this results =\nfrom the random walk assumption). As the market=0Amoves, so the option is i=\nn-the-money, a larger number of the possible outcomes=0Awill be positive, a=\nnd some highly positive outcomes become possible, so=0Athe expected value o=\nf the option will rise. Conversely, if the option moves=0Aout-of-the-money,=\n relatively few of the possible outcomes will be positive=0Areturns, and mo=\nre will be zero; this will cause the value of the option=0Ato decline.</P>=\n=0A=0A<P>The expected value of an option, then, is a function of two main e=\nlements:=0Athe <B><I>size</I></B> of the applicable distribution, which is =\na product=0Aof the time remaining before expiry, and the volatility expecte=\nd during=0Athat time; and the <B><I>location</I></B> of the distribution ve=\nrsus the=0Aoption's strike price, which is determined by the relationship b=\netween the=0Astrike and the current forward outright. The former establishe=\ns the range=0Aof possible outcomes and their probabilities, while the latte=\nr defines the=0Apay-off value of each outcome.</P>=0A=0A<P>A final element =\nin option pricing that should be mentioned is the <B><I>discount=0Afactor</=\nI></B>. An option&#146;s pay-off will be realised upon exercise;=0Athe prem=\nium is payable at the outset. If the premium is to be equal to the=0Aexpect=\ned value of the pay-off, it must be adjusted for the time value of=0Amoney;=\n the future number is discounted so that the present value of the=0Apremium=\n is equal to the present value of the pay-off. This makes option=0Apremiums=\n moderately susceptible to changes in interest rates (apart from=0Athe effe=\nct that interest rate changes have on forward outright rates).</P>=0A=0A<P>=\nThe full description, then, is that an option premium equals <B><I>the=0Apr=\nobability-weighted sum of all its possible pay-offs at expiry, discounted=\n=0Ato the present</I></B>. Option pricing models such as the famous Black-S=\ncholes=0Amodel use formula to calculate the expected value of an option bas=\ned on=0Athese factors.</P>=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#Top\">...Back to contents</A>=\n=0A=0A<A NAME=3D\"Exotic\"></a><p>=0A<hr>=0A<H2><CENTER>Exotic Options</CENTE=\nR></H2>=0A=0A<P>Exotic options are defined as such when their pay-off profi=\nle differs=0Afrom that of a standard currency option. The most commonly use=\nd exotic options=0Aare described below.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Path-Dependent Options=\n</H3>=0A=0A<P>An option whose pay-off depends upon the path that the spot r=\nate travels=0Aover the lifetime of the option between inception and expiry.=\n</P>=0A=0A<H3>Barrier Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>The largest and most actively tr=\naded group of exotic options. Barrier=0Aoptions are activated (knocked-in) =\nand become exerciseable or are terminated=0A(knocked-out) and cease to be e=\nxerciseable if a specific trigger level is=0Areached before or on the expir=\ny date. As the barrier option will not necessarily=0Aexist for the full mat=\nurity period of the option or may never be activated,=0Abarrier options com=\nmand a lower premium than conventional or &#145;vanilla&#146;=0Aoptions. Th=\nere are two main types of barrier options, namely:</P>=0A=0A<H3>Standard Kn=\nock-Out and Knock-In Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>The option is activated (knocked-=\nin) and becomes capable of exercise=0Aor terminated (knocked-out) and becom=\nes incapable of exercise as the option=0Ais moving out-of-the-money. In thi=\ns case the barrier level would be below=0Athe spot rate for a Call and abov=\ne the spot rate for a Put. For these options,=0Athe premium reduction is a =\nfunction of the trigger level. The more likely=0Athe option contract is to =\nbe knocked-out or the less likely it is to be=0Aknocked-in, the greater the=\n premium reduction and vice versa.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Reverse Knock-Out and Knock=\n-In Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>The option is activated (knocked-in) and becomes c=\napable of exercise=0Aor terminated (knocked-out) and becomes incapable of e=\nxercise as the option=0Ais moving further into-the-money. In this case the =\nbarrier level would be=0Aabove the spot rate for a Call and below the spot =\nrate for a Put. Due to=0Athe quite different features of the reverse barrie=\nrs versus the standard=0Abarriers, the former are priced and behave quite d=\nifferently from the latter.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Average Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>The p=\nricing of the option depends on an averaging process and there are=0Atwo di=\nstinct types:</P>=0A=0A<H3>Average Rate Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>The option is =\ncash settled at expiry by comparing the strike price with=0Athe average of =\na pre-determined series of spot rates, observed over the=0Alifetime of the =\noption. There is an associated premium saving over the standard=0Aor &#145;=\nvanilla&#146; option as the averaging process smoothes out the=0Aspot movem=\nents, thereby reducing volatility and hence the premium of the=0Aoption.</P>=\n=0A=0A<H3>Average Strike Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>The option differs from the Av=\nerage Rate Option in that the strike price=0Ais not set until the expiry da=\nte. It is then set to equal the average of=0Aa pre-determined series of spo=\nt rates observed over the lifetime of the=0Aoption. The Average Strike Opti=\non is then exercised against the spot rate=0Aprevailing at expiry and can b=\ne either cash or physically settled.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Look-Back Options</H3>=0A=\n=0A<P>The option allows the holder to &#145;look back&#146; over the lifeti=\nme=0Aof the option and transact at the most favourable exchange rate that h=\nas=0Aoccurred during that time. There are two distinct types:</P>=0A=0A<H3>=\nOptimal Rate Lookback Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>The strike is fixed on the initia=\nl deal date, and at expiry the option=0Awill pay out against the highest (f=\nor a Call) or lowest (for a Put), spot=0Afixing rate over the option&#146;s=\n lifetime, regardless of the spot rate=0Aprevailing at expiry. The option i=\ns usually cash settled. As the option=0Ahas the potential for a larger pay-=\noff than the standard vanilla option,=0Athe option premium will be greater =\nthan that of the equivalent vanilla option.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Optimal Strike Loo=\nkback Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>This differs from the Optimal Rate Lookback in th=\nat the strike price=0Ais not fixed until the expiry date of the option. The=\n strike is then fixed=0Aas the high (for a Put) or the low (for a Call) of =\nthe spot rate over the=0Aoption&#146;s lifetime. The option is then either =\ncash or physically settled=0Aagainst the spot rate prevailing at expiry.</P>=\n=0A=0A<H3>Digital (Binary) Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>An option whose pay-out is =\ndiscontinuous. A premium is payable at inception;=0Athen, if certain condit=\nions are satisfied, the pay-out will be a fixed,=0Apre-determined amount of=\n money. Once the pre-determined conditions have=0Abeen satisfied, the pay-o=\nut remains fixed, regardless of where the underlying=0Acurrency subsequentl=\ny trades. If the conditions are not satisfied, then=0Athe option pays out n=\nothing.</P>=0A=0A<H3>At-Maturity Digitals (European Digitals)</H3>=0A=0A<P>=\nA Digital Option that pays out a fixed amount if the spot trades above=0A(o=\nr below) a certain level at expiry, and pays nothing if spot does not=0Atra=\nde above (or below) that level at expiry.</P>=0A=0A<H3>One-Touch Digitals (=\nAmerican Digitals)</H3>=0A=0A<P>A Digital Option that pays out a fixed amou=\nnt if the spot rate trades=0Aabove (or below) a certain level at any time u=\np to and including the expiry=0Adate. The pre-determined pay-out amount can=\n be payable either at that time,=0Aor at expiry, depending on the terms of =\nthe option when it was entered into.</P>=0A=0A<P>The conditions that will d=\netermine a digital option&#146;s pay-out may=0Abe of several types: a spot =\nrate trading (or not trading), a range maintained=0A(or broken), a level tr=\nading only after another level trades, and many more.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Correlat=\nion Dependent Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>An option whose pay-off depends on the c=\norrelation between two or more=0Acurrencies or asset classes.</P>=0A=0A<H3>=\nBasket Options</H3>=0A=0A<P>An option whose pay-off is related to the perfo=\nrmance of a basket of=0Acurrencies. Typically, the option will have a singl=\ne Call (Put) currency=0Aand a basket of Put (Call) currencies. The proporti=\nons of these currencies=0Awill be specified in advance to suit the client's=\n individual needs.</P>=0A=0A<P>At maturity, the option&#146;s value is dete=\nrmined by calculating the=0Abasket spot rate and comparing that with the st=\nrike price. The option can=0Abe either cash or physically settled. The prem=\nium reduction depends on the=0Anumber of currencies and the composition of =\nthe basket involved, and the=0Acorrelations between the constituent currenc=\nies of the basket and the Call=0A(Put) currency.</P>=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#To=\np\">...Back to contents</A>=0A=0A<A NAME=3D\"Structured\"></a><p>=0A<hr>=0A=0A=\n=0A<H2><CENTER>Structured Currency Products</CENTER></H2>=0A=0A<P>Structure=\nd currency products are combinations of vanilla and exotic=0Aoptions, and u=\nse &#147;<B><I>building blocks</I></B>&#148;=0Ato create payoffs to suit th=\ne customer&#146;s specific needs=0Aand views on the market. Some of the mos=\nt commonly used structures are listed=0Abelow.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Trigger Forward=\n</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Trigger Forward structure is primarily designed for tradi=\nng purposes,=0Aalthough it can be used as an alternative &#145;hedge&#146; =\nfor a cash position=0Aas well. It is a zero cost structure, whereby the pur=\nchaser enters into=0Aa synthetic forward contract at a rate significantly m=\nore attractive than=0Athe prevailing market rate, but whereby the whole str=\nucture knocks out if=0Aa pre-determined trigger level (set in-the-money in =\nrelation to the forward=0Arate) is reached at any time before the expiry of=\n the structure.</P>=0A=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/trigger_fwd.gi=\nf\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=0ANATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></=\nP>=0A=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/trigger_fwd_pls_cash.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HE=\nIGHT=3D\"298\" =0AALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\" NATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<=\nP>The product could be of interest to those looking for a limited move=0Aon=\n the underlying in their favour, and who think that the knock-out level=0Ai=\ns unlikely to trade.</P>=0A=0A<P>It should be noted that the contract is a =\nsynthetic forward contract,=0Aand therefore one would be obliged to buy (se=\nll) the underlying if the market=0Awere to trade unfavourably. The potentia=\nl benefit to a hedger is that one=0Ais able to cover the exposure at a more=\n favourable rate than the current=0Aforward; if however, the trigger level =\nis reached, the hedge ceases to exist,=0Aleaving the exposure unhedged in a=\nn unfavourable market.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Forward Extra</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Forward =\nExtra structure has been developed primarily for hedging=0Apurposes, and is=\n essentially a vanilla option that becomes a synthetic forward=0Acontract i=\nf a trigger level (set out-of-the-money in relation to the forward=0Arate) =\nis reached at any time before the option expiry.</P>=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG S=\nRC=3D\"../images/fwd_xtra.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=\n=0ANATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/fwd_xtra_pls_ca=\nsh.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D=0A\"BOTTOM\" NATURALSIZEFLAG=3D=\n\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>For zero cost, the purchaser of the structure acq=\nuires protection for=0Aany adverse exchange rate move - albeit at a rate so=\nmewhat worse than the=0Aforward outright - and can benefit from a favourabl=\ne but limited move on=0Athe underlying (provided that the trigger level is =\nnot hit).</P>=0A=0A<P>If the trigger level is reached, then the hedger woul=\nd be obliged to=0Atransact at the unfavourable synthetic forward rate. The =\nproduct has proved=0Ato be a popular alternative hedging tool, because it p=\nrovides protection=0Awhilst offering the potential to outperform considerab=\nly the prevailing=0Aforward outright rate for zero cost.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Weekl=\ny Reset Forward</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Weekly Reset Forward structure has been de=\nveloped for both trading=0Aand hedging purposes. It is a synthetic forward,=\n where each portion of the=0Acontract needs to be activated on a weekly bas=\nis. For each week that the=0Apre-established &#145;fixing&#146; condition i=\ns satisfied, a portion of=0Athe contract is locked in.</P>=0A<center>=0A<P>=\n<IMG SRC=3D\"../images/wkly_reset_fwd.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIG=\nN=3D=0A\"BOTTOM\" NATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/wk=\nly_reset_fwd_plus_cash.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\"=0AALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=\n NATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>If none of the weekly conditio=\nns is satisfied, then none of the contract=0Ais activated. If all the weekl=\ny conditions are satisfied, then the currency=0Ais bought (sold) at a more =\nfavourable outright rate than the initial prevailing=0Amarket rate. The pro=\nduct is an interesting alternative for those with cash=0Aflows spread over =\na period of time, or for balance sheet hedgers.</P>=0A=0A<P>It provides an =\nopportunity to deal at a rate significantly better than=0Athe forward outri=\nght, but only for a portion of the amount corresponding=0Ato the frequency =\nthat spot has fixed above (below) a pre-determined trigger=0Alevel.</P>=0A=\n=0A<H3>Mini-Premium Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Mini-Premium Option structure h=\nas been developed mainly for hedging=0Apurposes. It is a structure for whic=\nh no initial premium is paid; if, subsequently,=0Apre-determined spot level=\ns are traded, certain fixed premiums will be payable=0Aby the option holder=\n at the maturity of the option.</P>=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/m=\nini_premium_option.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D=0A\"BOTTOM\" NA=\nTURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/mini_premium_optn_pl=\nus_cash.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D=0A\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\" NATURALSIZEFL=\nAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>The product offers a potentially zero cost s=\ntructure for hedgers, but=0Aif all the trigger levels are traded, the custo=\nmer pays a higher premium=0Athan the equivalent vanilla option.</P>=0A=0A<P=\n>However, for these trigger levels to have traded, the spot would have=0Amo=\nved in favour of the hedger&#146;s underlying position.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Range =\nBinary</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Range Binary structure has been developed primarily=\n for trading purposes=0Aand will profit if the spot rate stays within a ran=\nge. A currency range=0Ais specified by the customer over a fixed period.</P>=\n=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/range_binary.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIG=\nHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=0ANATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>A=\n premium is paid up front and provided that the spot stays within the=0Aran=\nge (as monitored on a 24-hour basis), then a multiple of the premium=0Apaid=\n will be payable to the holder. If, however, either limit of the range=0Ais=\n traded before expiry, then no pay-out will be due and the premium is=0Afor=\nfeited. The product can be used on its own as a currency play for range-tra=\nding=0Amarkets or <STRONG>combined with a deposit as a yield enhancement st=\nructure</STRONG>.</P>=0A=0A<H3>Wall Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>The Wall Option str=\nucture has been developed primarily for trading purposes.=0AIt profits to t=\nhe extent a spot rate stays below (above) a certain pre-determined=0Alevel.=\n The customer specifies a currency rate, and pays a premium up front.</P>=\n=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/wall_option.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGH=\nT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=0ANATURALSIZEFLAG=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>Fo=\nr every day during a set period that the spot fixes above (below) the=0Aspe=\ncified rate, a portion of the pay-out is locked-in. If spot fixes below=0A(=\nabove) the trigger level every day, then the maximum pay-out will be due;=\n=0Aif none of the days satisfies the required condition, then no pay-out wi=\nll=0Abe due. The product can be used on its own as a currency play for a cu=\nstomer=0Awith a view on the market&#146;s direction, or like the corridor a=\nnd range=0Abinary options, <B>combined with a deposit for a potential yield=\n - enhancement=0Astructure.</B></P>=0A=0A<H3>Corridor Option</H3>=0A=0A<P>T=\nhe Corridor Option structure has been designed primarily for trading=0Apurp=\noses. It profits to the extent that spot stays within a range and is=0Aofte=\nn linked with a deposit for yield - enhancement purposes. The customer=0Asp=\necifies a currency range, and pays a premium up front. For every day during=\n=0Aa set period that the spot fixes within the specified range, a portion of=\n=0Athe pay-out is locked in.</P>=0A<center>=0A<P><IMG SRC=3D\"../images/corr=\nidor.gif\" WIDTH=3D\"364\" HEIGHT=3D\"298\" ALIGN=3D\"BOTTOM\"=0ANATURALSIZEFLAG=\n=3D\"3\"></P>=0A</center>=0A<P>If spot fixes within the range every day, then=\n the maximum pay-out will=0Abe due; if not a single day fixes within the ra=\nnge then the pay-out will=0Abe zero. The actual pay-out is calculated on a =\npro-rata basis. The product=0Ais similar to the range binary in that both w=\nill profit if a spot rate stays=0Awithin a range. The difference is that, w=\nhereas the range binary structure=0Ais terminated if either of the boundari=\nes trade at any time, the corridor=0Aoption structure exists for the whole =\nmaturity period, with only the pay-out=0Afor that day forfeited should spot=\n trade outside the range. As the corridor=0Aoption has a less aggressive ri=\nsk profile, its maximum pay-out will be smaller=0Athan for the equivalent r=\nange binary.</P>=0A=0A<P><A HREF=3D\"#Top\">...Back to contents</A>=0A=0A=0A=\n=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A<p><!-- #BeginLibraryItem \"/Library/BackButton.lbi\" --=\n><a href=3D\"http://www.sembrador.net/\" onClick=3D\"history.go(-1);return fal=\nse;\" onMouseOver=3D\"window.status=3D'Back'; return true;\" onMouseOut=3D\"win=\ndow.status=3D''; return true;\" class=3D\"navlink\"><img src=3D\"../GStore/imag=\ne/back.gif\" width=3D\"61\" height=3D\"23\" border=3D\"0\" align=3D\"absmiddle\"><br=\n></a><!-- #EndLibraryItem --></p>=0A=0A=0A</BODY>=0A</HTML>=0A<!-- text bel=\now generated by server.                                 Medicare Coverage Criteria<br>=0A         =\n                         <br>=0A                                  </b>A pow=\ner operated vehicle (POV) is covered =0A                                  w=\nhen <b>all</b> of the following criteria are =0A                           =\n       met:<br>=0A                                  <br>=0A                =\n                  1.&nbsp; The patient's condition is such that =0A        =\n                          a wheelchair is required for the patient to =0A  =\n                                get around in the home,<br>=0A             =\n                     <br>=0A                                  2.&nbsp; The =\npatient is unable to operate a =0A                                  manual =\nwheelchair,<br>=0A                                  <br>=0A                =\n                  3.&nbsp; The patient is capable of safely operating =0A  =\n                                the controls for the POV, and<br>=0A       =\n                           <br>=0A                                  4.&nbsp=\n; The patient can transfer safely in =0A                                  a=\nnd out of the POV and has adequate trunk stability =0A                     =\n             to be able to safely ride in the POV.<br>=0A                  =\n                <br>=0A                                  Most POVs are orde=\nred for patients who are <u>capable =0A                                  of=\n ambulation within the home</u> but require =0A                            =\n      a power vehicle for movement outside the home. =0A                   =\n               POVs will be <b>denied as not medically necessary</b> =0A   =\n                               in these circumstances.<br>=0A              =\n                    A POV that is beneficial primarily in allowing =0A     =\n                             the patient to perform leisure or recreational =\n=0A                                  activities will be denied as not medic=\nally necessary.<br>=0A                                  If a POV is covered=\n, a wheelchair provided at =0A                                  the same ti=\nme or subsequently will usually be =0A                                  den=\nied as not medically necessary.<br>=0A                                  A P=\nOV is usually covered only if it is ordered =0A                            =\n      by a physician who is one of the following specialties: =0A          =\n                        Physical Medicine, Orthopedic Surgery, Neurology, =\n=0A                                  or Rheumatology.     =\n                       is also indicated for the treatment=0A              =\n                                of patients with advanced disease=0A       =\n (ARC).=0A                                              The evaluatio=\nn of the benefit risk=0A                                              relat=\nionship, based on present=0A size=3D\"2\"><b>PHARMACOKINETICS=0A  =\n                                              AND PHARMACODINAMICS: </b></f=\nont></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" clas=\ns=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">PHAR=\nMACOKINETICS:=0A                                              At all the le=\nvels of dose studied,=0A                                              the z=\nidovudine is well absorbed=0A                                              =\nin the intestine; bioavailability=0A                                       =\n       is 60-70%; mean plasma concentrations=0A                            =\n                  at steady state, maxima (Ossmax)=0A                      =\n                        and minima (Ossmin), following=0A                  =\n                            the administration of zidovudine=0A            =\n                                  oral (in solution) at doses 5 mg=0A      =\n                                        per Kg of body weight every 4 hours,=\n=0A                                              were 1.9 and 0.1 mg/mL res=\npectively.=0A                                              Available data i=\ns limited but it=0A                                              suggest th=\nat Ossmax and Ossmin=0A                                              levels=\n following a 200-mg dose=0A                                              ev=\nery 4 hours, are approximately=0A                                          =\n    1.0 and &lt; 0.1 mg/ml respectively,=0A                                =\n              corresponding levels after a 250-mg=0A                       =\n                       dose every 4 hours are 1.2 and=0A                   =\n                           0.2 mg/ml respectively. </font></p>=0A          =\n                                <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font=\n face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">In=0A                    =\n                          studies with zidovudine, administered=0A         =\n                                     by intravenous route, the plasma=0A   =\n                                           half-life is approximately 1.1=\n=0A                                              hours. Clearance of zidovu=\ndine=0A                                              exceeds by far that of=\n creatinine,=0A                                              thus indicatin=\ng that there is tubular=0A                                              sec=\nretion. <br>=0A        The 5-glucuronide of zidovudine is the main plasma a=\nnd urinary metabolite,=0A        and it accounts for 50 to 60% of the admin=\nistered dose eliminated by=0A        renal excretion; no other metabolites =\nhave been observed. <br>=0A        There is limited data about pharmacokine=\ntics of zidovudine in children=0A        and in patients with renal or hepa=\ntic damage (see Administration). There=0A        is no data about the pharm=\nacokinetics of zidovudine in the elderly. Levels=0A        of zidovudine in=\n cephalorachidian liquid correspond approximately to=0A        50% of plasm=\na levels following the chronic administration. The limited=0A        availa=\nble data suggest that zidovudine crosses the placenta and appears=0A       =\n in the amniotic liquid and fetal blood. Zidovudine has also been detected=\n=0A        in semen. <br>=0A        The bond to plasma proteins is relative=\nly low (from 36% to 38%), and=0A        thus no pharmacological interaction=\ns that involve any displacement from=0A        sites of binding are expecte=\nd. </font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left=\n\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2=\n\"><b>CONTRAINDICATIONS:</b></font></p>=0A                                  =\n        <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetic=\na, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">ZIDOVIR=0A                                       =\n       is contraindicated in patients=0A                                   =\n           with known hypersensitivity to=0A                               =\n               zidovudine. ZIDOVIR should not=0A                           =\n                   be administered to patients having=0A                   =\n                           an abnormally low count of neutrophiles=0A      =\n                                        (less than 0.75 x 10-9 /ml) or=0A  =\n                                            abnormally low levels of hemogl=\nobin=0A                                              (less than 7.5 g/dL). =\n</font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" c=\nlass=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> =\n<b>PRECAUTIONS=0A                                                OR RESTRIC=\nTIONS OF USE DURING=0A                                                PREGN=\nANCY AND LACTATION:</b></font></p>=0A                                      =\n    <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, s=\nans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">It=0A                                              is=\n not known if zidovudine can=0A                                            =\n  affect human fecundity, or if it=0A                                      =\n        may cause damage if administered=0A                                =\n              during pregnancy. Use of zidovudine=0A                       =\n                       during pregnancy should be considered=0A            =\n                                  only if it is perfectly indicated=0A     =\n                                         or when potential benefits of the=\n=0A                                              treatment for the mother o=\nutweigh=0A                                              any possible risk f=\nor the developing=0A                                              fetus. </=\nfont></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" cla=\nss=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>=\nLactation:</b> There=0A                                              is lim=\nited data indicating that=0A                                              z=\nidovudine is excreted in the animal=0A                                     =\n         milk (Ruprecht et al, 1988). It=0A                                =\n              is unknown if zidovudine is excreted=0A                      =\n                        in human milk. Since the drug can=0A               =\n                               appear in the human milk and may=0A         =\n                                     cause serious toxicity to breast-feedi=\nng=0A                                              newborn, it is recommend=\ned that=0A                                              mothers given ZIDOV=\nIR do not feed=0A                                              their babies=\n. </font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\"=\n class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"=\n> <b>ADVERSE=0A                                                REACTIONS:</=\nb></font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\"=\n class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"=\n>The=0A                                              most frequent and impo=\nrtant adverse=0A                                              reactions inc=\nlude anemia (that=0A                                              often nee=\nds blood transfusion),=0A                                              neut=\nropenia and leucopenia. These=0A                                           =\n   occur with higher frequency at=0A                                       =\n       high doses (1,200 to 1,500 mg/day)=0A                               =\n               and in patients with advanced disease=0A                    =\n                          by HVI. In patients with &lt; 100=0A             =\n                                 T4 helpers / mm3 it may be necessary=0A   =\n                                           a reduction of the dose or disco=\nntinuation=0A                                              of treatment (se=\ne Dose and Administration=0A                                              R=\noute); incidence of neutropenia=0A                                         =\n     also increased in patients with=0A                                    =\n          previous neutropenia or in patients=0A                           =\n                   with low levels of vitamin B12=0A                       =\n                       and anemia, and in patients under=0A                =\n                              concomitant paracetamol (see Drug=0A         =\n                                     interactions). <br>=0A        Other ad=\nverse reaction reported in controlled clinical trials with placebo=0A      =\n  include: nausea, vomit, anorexia, abdominal pain, cephalea, cutaneous=0A =\n       eruption, fever, myalgia, paresthesia, insomnia, malaise, asthenia, =\nand=0A        dyspepsia. Besides the nausea, the most common and significan=\nt adverse=0A        effect in all the studies with zidovudine, other report=\ned adverse effects=0A        were not consistent compared with placebo. The=\n most common adverse effects=0A        reported in patients with advanced d=\nisease by HIV were severe headache,=0A        myalgia, and insomnia, howeve=\nr vomit, anorexia, malaise and asthenia=0A        were most common in patie=\nnts with early disease by HIV. <br>=0A        Other recorded adverse effect=\ns included drowsiness, diarrhea, dizziness,=0A        perspiration, dyspnea=\n, flatulence, taste alteration, pain in the chest,=0A        loss of mental=\n acuteness, depression, generalized pain, chills, cough,=0A        hives, p=\nruritus, and pseudogrippal syndrome. <br>=0A        Incidence of these and =\nother less common reactions were similar in both=0A        groups under stu=\ndy. <br>=0A        The following events have been reported in patients trea=\nted with ZIDOVIR.=0A        They also can occur as part of the underlying p=\nrocess of the disease.=0A        Thus, the relationship of these reactions =\nwith the use of ZIDOVIR is=0A        hard to evaluate, particularly in the =\ncomplicated cases that characterize=0A        an advanced infection by HIV.=\n </font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" =\nclass=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">-=\n=0A                                              Convulsions and other cere=\nbral=0A                                              problems.<br>=0A      =\n  - Myopathy.<br>=0A        - Ungual pigmentation.<br>=0A        - Pancytop=\nenia with medullar hypoplasia and isolated thrombocytopenia. <br>=0A       =\n - Hepatic disorders with increase in transaminases and bilirubin levels. <=\n/font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" cl=\nass=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> <=\nb>DRUG=0A                                                INTERACTIONS:</b><=\n/font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" cl=\nass=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">Be=\ncause=0A                                              of the limited experi=\nence with=0A                                              zidovudine and it=\ns interactions=0A                                              with other d=\nrugs, caution should=0A                                              be exe=\nrcised when administering=0A                                              c=\noncomitantly ZIDOVIR and other=0A                                          =\n    drugs. <br>=0A        The interactions stated below should not be consi=\ndered absolute but representatives=0A        of the medicaments for which c=\naution should be exercised. <br>=0A        It has been reported low blood l=\nevels of phenytoin in some patients given=0A        zidovudine, although it=\n was observed an increased level in one patient.=0A        These observatio=\nns suggest that plasma levels of phenytoin should be=0A        carefully mo=\nnitored in patients that receive both drugs. <br>=0A        The concomitant=\n use of paracetamol during the treatment with ZIDOVIR=0A        increases t=\nhe incidence of neutropenia, especially after a chronic treatment,=0A      =\n  presumably because of the reduction in zidovudine metabolism. <br>=0A    =\n    Other drugs (such as acetylsalicylic acid, codeine, morphine, indometha=\ncin,=0A        ketoprofen, naproxen, oxazepam, lorazepam, cimetidine, clorf=\nibrate, dapsone,=0A        and isoprinosine) may also alter the metabolism =\nof zidovudine by competitively=0A        inhibiting the glucuronidation or =\ndirect inhibition of the hepatic microsomal=0A        metabolism. <br>=0A  =\n      Before the use of these drugs the interactions should be evaluated ca=\nrefully,=0A        particularly during the chronic therapy in combination w=\nith ZIDOVIR. <br>=0A        The concomitant use with potentially nephrotoxi=\nc or myelosuppressive=0A        drugs (such as systemic pentamidine, dapson=\ne, pirimethamine, amphotericin,=0A        flucitocine, gancyclovir, interfe=\nron, vinchristine, vinblastine, and=0A        doxorubicine) may also increa=\nse the risk of toxicity with ZIDOVIR. <br>=0A        Some antiviral analogs=\n of nucleosides (e.g. ribavirine) antagonize in=0A        vitro the antivir=\nal activity of zidovudine and therefor the simultaneous=0A        use of su=\nch drugs should be avoided. <br>=0A        Since some patients given zidovu=\ndine may continue experiencing opportunistic=0A        infections, it shoul=\nd be considered the concomitant use of an antimicrobial=0A        therapy w=\nith co-trimoxazol, pentamidine in aerosol, pirimethamine, and=0A        acy=\nclovir. <br>=0A        The available data do not indicate increase in the r=\nisk of toxicity with=0A        the use of these drugs. <br>=0A        There=\n is little data suggesting that probenecid, by reducing glucuronidation,=0A=\n        raises the half-life and the area under the curve for the plasma co=\nncentration=0A        of zidovudine. The renal excretion of glucuronide (an=\nd possibly zidovudine=0A        itself) is decreased in presence of probene=\ncid. </font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"le=\nft\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D=\n\"2\"> <b>ALTERATIONS=0A                                                OF LA=\nBORATORY TESTS:</b></font></p>=0A                                          =\n<p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-=\nserif\" size=3D\"2\">There=0A                                              are=\n no reports of alteration in=0A                                            =\n  laboratory tests. </font></p>=0A                                         =\n <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans=\n-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> <b>PRECAUTIONS=0A                                      =\n          AND RELATION WITH CARCINOGENIC,=0A                               =\n                 MUTAGENIC, TERATOGENIC, AND FERTILITY=0A                  =\n                              EFFECTS:</b></font></p>=0A                   =\n                       <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"=\nArial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">Patients=0A                       =\n                       should be warned about the use=0A                   =\n                           of drugs not prescribed by their=0A             =\n                                 physicians (see Drug interactions).=0A    =\n                                          Zidovudine has not shown reduction=\n=0A                                              in the risk of HIV transmi=\nssion=0A                                              through sexual interc=\nourse or contamination=0A                                              with=\n blood and its derivatives. </font></p>=0A                                 =\n         <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helveti=\nca, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>CARCINOGENESIS:</b><br>=0A        Zidovudine =\nwas administered in three levels of dosage by oral route to=0A            r=\nats and mice (60 females and 60 males per group), at initial single=0A     =\n       doses of 30, 60, and 120 mg/Kg/day and 80, 220 and 600 mg/Kg/day=0A =\n           to mice and rats respectively. After day 90th, doses in mice gro=\nup=0A            were reduced to 20, 30 and 40 mg/Kg/day because of anemia =\nrelated=0A            to treatment, only the highest dose was reduced for r=\nats (to 450=0A            and then to 300 mg/Kg/day at days 91st and 279th =\nrespectively). <br>=0A        With the highest dose, mice showed 7 neoplasm=\ns of late appearance (after=0A        19 months; 5 squamous cell carcinomas=\n, one squamous cell papilloma, and=0A        one squamous polyp). One squam=\nous cell polyp of late appearance occurred=0A        in the vagina of one a=\nnimal treated with the medium dose. With the lowest=0A        dose there we=\nre no presence of vaginal tumors. <br>=0A        With the highest dose, rat=\ns showed two squamous cell carcinomas of late=0A        appearance (after 2=\n0 months) in the vagina. With the medium and lowest=0A        dose there we=\nre no presence of vaginal tumors. <br>=0A        No other tumors related wi=\nth the drug were observed in both species and=0A        for both sexes. <br>=\n=0A        The value of carcinogenesis studies in rodents, to predict carci=\nnogenesis=0A        in man, is uncertain and thus the clinical relevance of=\n these findings=0A        is not clear. </font></p>=0A                     =\n                     <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Ar=\nial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>MUTAGENESIS:</b><br>=0A        In=\n the test of Ames there is no evidence of mutagenesis; however, zidovudine=\n=0A            was slightly mutagenic in one assay with lymphoma cells of m=\nouse,=0A            and it was positive in one assay of cell transformation=\n in vitro.=0A            Clastic effects (damage to chromosomes) were obser=\nved in one in vitro=0A            study with human lymphocytes and in micro=\nnucleus studies in vivo=0A            with repeated oral doses given to mic=\ne and rats. <br>=0A        One cytogenic study in vivo with rats, failed to=\n show chromosomal damage. <br>=0A        The clinical relevance of these fi=\nndings is not significant. </font></p>=0A                                  =\n        <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetic=\na, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>TERATOGENESIS:</b><br>=0A        Studies with =\npregnant rats and does, which were given zidovudine by oral=0A            r=\noute in doses up to 450 and 500 mg/Kg/day respectively during the=0A       =\n     main period of organogenesis, have not revealed evidence of teratogene=\nsis.=0A            However, in rats given 150 to 450 mg/Kg/day and in does =\nwith 500=0A            mg/Kg/day dose, there was an statistically significa=\nnt increase in=0A            the incidence of fetal resorptions. </font></p>=\n=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"sto=\nrybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>FERTILITY=\n:</b><br>=0A        Zidovudine did not alter the fertility of male or femal=\ne rats that received=0A            oral doses up to 450 mg/Kg/day. </font><=\n/p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"=\nstorybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>DOSE=\n=0A                                                AND ADMINISTRATION ROUTE=\n:</b></font></p>=0A                                          <p align=3D\"le=\nft\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D=\n\"2\"><b>ADULTS:</b><br>=0A        For a mean patient with 70 Kg, it is recom=\nmended an initial oral dose=0A            of 200 mg of zidovudine every 4 h=\nours (1,200 mg/day). <br>=0A        A great number of doses have been used,=\n usually between 500 and 1,500=0A        mg/day. Optimum dose has not been =\nestablished yet, and it may vary from=0A        patient to patient. In the =\npractice many patients can be maintained adequately=0A        with doses of=\n 1,000 mg/day divided in 4 or 5 doses. <br>=0A        In particular cases a=\n lower dose can be chosen, depending on the stage=0A        of the disease =\nand other relevant factors (such as the functioning of=0A        the marrow=\nbone or patient body weight). <br>=0A        It is unknown the efficacy of =\nlower doses for the treatment or prevention=0A        of neural dysfunction=\ns related to HIV and neoplasias. <br>=0A        For patients with hematolog=\nical toxicity it may be necessary to adjust=0A        the posology. Especia=\nlly in those with marrowbone dysfunction previous=0A        to treatment, p=\narticularly in patients with advanced disease by HIV.=0A        If hemoglob=\nin level decreases to values between 7.5 and 9 g/dl or the=0A        count =\nof neutrophils decreases to values between 0.75 x 10 /L and 1.0=0A        x=\n 10 /L, then the daily dose can be divided (example, the recommended=0A    =\n    total daily dose can be administered every 8 hours) until there is evid=\nence=0A        of marrowbone recovery. Then the posology can be increased u=\nntil the=0A        original dose is reached. Alternatively, marrowbone reco=\nvery can be improved=0A        by the brief interruption (2 to 4 weeks) of =\nzidovudine therapy. <br>=0A        The treatment must be interrupted if hem=\noglobin value falls below 7.5=0A        g/dl or the count of neutrophils is=\n less than 0.75 x 10 /L. Recovery=0A        is usually observed within two =\nweeks, after this period the treatment=0A        with zidovudine may be res=\numed at reduced doses (i.e. the recommended=0A        daily dose divided in=\n 3 doses or every 8 hours). After 2 to 4 weeks the=0A        dose can be in=\ncreased gradually depending on patient&#146;s tolerance,=0A        until th=\ne original posology is reached. </font></p>=0A                             =\n             <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>C=\nHILDREN:</b><br>=0A        There is limited data about the use of zidovudin=\ne in children. Even though=0A            they are not experimental, initial=\n doses of 150 to 180 mg/m2 every=0A            6 hours (four times a day) h=\nave been employed widely.</font></p>=0A                                    =\n      <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>ELDER:</=\nb><br>=0A        There is no data about the use of zidovudine in elder, but=\n due to the=0A            diminished renal function related to age, it is a=\ndvised especial=0A            attention in this kind of patients. </font></=\np>=0A                                          <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helv=\netica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>RENAL=0A                                  =\n              DAMAGE:</b><br>=0A        The limited available data for pati=\nents with diminished renal function=0A        do not suggest the particular=\n need of adjusting initial dose, because=0A        zidovudine levels do not=\n increase significantly.<br>=0A        In case of renal failure it can be e=\nxpected an accumulation of the glucuronide=0A        metabolite, however, t=\nhe effect of such an accumulation is unknown. The=0A        monitoring of p=\nlasma levels of zidovudine (and its glucuronide metabolite),=0A        toge=\nther with hematological parameters, may indicate the need of limited=0A    =\n    adjustment for the elimination of the glucuronide metabolite. </font></=\np>=0A                                          <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helv=\netica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>HEPATIC=0A                                =\n                DAMAGE:</b><br>=0A        The limited available data for pa=\ntients with cirrhosis suggest that in=0A        case of hepatic failure, it=\n can occur accumulation of zidovudine due=0A        to the reduced glucuron=\nidation. It may be necessary to adjust the dose,=0A        at present it is=\n not possible to make precise recommendations. If it=0A        is not possi=\nble the monitoring of plasma levels of zidovudine, then the=0A        physi=\ncians will need to look for intolerance signs and increase the period=0A   =\n     of time between doses as necessary. </font></p>=0A                    =\n                      <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=\n=3D\"2\"> <b>OVERDOSAGE=0A                                                OR =\nACCIDENTAL INTAKE; SYMPTOMS=0A                                             =\n   AND HANDLING (ANTIDOTES):</b><br>=0A        Symptoms and signs: There is=\n limited available information about the=0A        acute intake of overdose=\ns and its consequences. No specific symptoms=0A        related to overdose =\nhave been identified. <br>=0A        Oral doses up to 1,250 mg of ZIDOVIR e=\nvery four hours during four weeks=0A        have been administered to two p=\natients with advanced disease, one did=0A        not show adverse effects. =\n<br>=0A        Treatment: Patients should be closely monitored to detect an=\ny possible=0A        evidence of toxicity (see Adverse reactions) and shoul=\nd receive any necessary=0A        supporting therapy. <br>=0A        Hemodi=\nalysis has a limited effect on the elimination of zidovudine, but=0A       =\n improves the elimination of the glucuronide metabolite. </font></p>=0A    =\n                                      <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sa=\nns-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> <b>HOW=0A                                            =\n    SUPPLIED:</b><br>=0A        Bottle with 100 capsules of 100 mg.<br>=0A =\n       Bottle with 30 capsules of 250 mg.<br>=0A        Carton with 100 cap=\nsules of 100 mg.<br>=0A        Carton with 30 capsules of 250 mg.</font></p>=\n=0A                                          <p><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvet=\nica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> <b>STORAGE:</b><br>=0A        Store in a dry a=\nnd cool place. </font></p>=0A                                          <p><=\nfont face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> <b>PROTECTIVE=0A    =\n                                            STATEMENTS:</b><br>=0A        L=\niterature exclusive for physicians. Do not administer t=\nhis=0A        medicine during pregnancy, lactation or children under 12 yea=\nrs of age.</font></p>=0A                                          <p><font =\nface=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>PRODUCT=0A             =\n                                   REGISTRATION NUMBER:</b><br>=0A        2=\n80M92 SSA<br>=0A        Prescribing Information Code<br>=0A        FEAR-129=\n85/93MR Trade Mark</font></p>=0A                                        </t=\nd>=0A                                      </tr>=0A                        =\n              <tr bgcolor=3D\"#CCFFCC\">=0A                                  =\n      <td colspan=3D\"2\">=0A                                          <p ali=\ngn=3Dleft class=3D\"storysubhead\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif=\n\" size=3D\"2\"><b>Doctor</b></font></p>=0A                                   =\n       <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica=\n, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> Zidovudine=0A                                    =\n          was the first FDA-approved antiretroviral=0A                     =\n                         drug. The patent for Zidovudine=0A                =\n                              expires in 2005. Despite the lack=0A         =\n                                     of a significant impact on morbidity=\n=0A                                              and mortality, it was used=\n at that=0A                                              time by many patie=\nnts as a single=0A                                              agent becau=\nse there were no other=0A                                              alte=\nrnatives. Without other agents=0A                                          =\n    with which to combine it, doses=0A                                     =\n         were often pushed much higher than=0A                             =\n                 the current dosage of 300 mg twice=0A                     =\n                         daily, leading many taking Zidovudine=0A          =\n                                    to experience significant nausea=0A    =\n                                          and vomiting. At current doses,=\n=0A                                              this occurs much less freq=\nuently,=0A                                              though another pote=\nntial side effect=0A                                              of Zidovu=\ndine, suppression of blood=0A                                              =\ncells (myelosuppression), remains.=0A                                      =\n        Resistance to Zidovudine often=0A                                  =\n            means resistance to other drugs=0A                             =\n                 in this class. Because it has a=0A                        =\n                      similar mechanism of action as=0A                    =\n                          Stavudine (d4T), these drugs should=0A           =\n                                   not be given together. For greater=0A   =\n                                           simplicity, Zidovudine is often=\n=0A                                              taken as Combivir (Zidovud=\nine and=0A                                              3TC in one pill) or=\n Trizivir (Zidovudine,=0A                                              3TC,=\n and abacavir in one pill).</font></p>=0A                                  =\n        <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetic=\na, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><i>-Jonathan=0A                                  =\n              Uy, MD</i></font></p>=0A                                     =\n   </td>=0A                                      </tr>=0A                  =\n                    <tr bgcolor=3D\"#CCFFFF\">=0A                            =\n            <td colspan=3D\"2\" bgcolor=3D\"#CCFFFF\">=0A                      =\n                    <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storysubhead\"><font face=3D\"=\nArial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><b>Activist</b></font></p>=0A     =\n                                     <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\">=\n<font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> (=0A               =\n                               Zidovudine) is the first drug approved=0A   =\n                                           for the treatment of AIDS. This=\n=0A                                              drug has taught the manufa=\ncturer,=0A                                              scientist and activ=\nist the importance=0A                                              of findi=\nng the most effective dose=0A                                              =\nto suppress the HIV virus with=0A                                          =\n    minimal side effects. Initially,=0A                                    =\n          Zidovudine was approved for treating=0A                          =\n                    HIV disease at a dose of 1200-1500=0A                  =\n                            mg a day. Further studies have=0A              =\n                                shown that a lower dose, ranging=0A        =\n                                      from 500-600 mg a day, was better=0A =\n                                             tolerated and achieved similar=\n=0A                                              suppression of the HIV vir=\nus than=0A                                              the approved higher=\n and more toxic=0A                                              dosage. The=\n majority of people=0A                                              taking =\nthis drug experience side=0A                                              e=\nffects that resolve over time.=0A                                          =\n    Zidovudine continues to serve as=0A                                    =\n          a cornerstone of HIV regimens mainly=0A                          =\n                    due to its synergistic effect with=0A                  =\n                            Epivir (3TC). Since Zidovudine=0A              =\n                                is the grandfather of HIV drugs=0A         =\n                                     approved in the USA, patients who=0A  =\n                                            are beginning therapy should ta=\nke=0A                                              a resistance test becaus=\ne approximately=0A                                              10% of pati=\nents may have acquired=0A                                              a vi=\nrus that is resistant to Zidovudine.</font></p>=0A                         =\n                 <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"byline\"><font face=3D\"Arial, He=\nlvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">-Charles=0A                                =\n              A. triphosphate compounds. BEC is a =0A                                              st=\nandardized mixture of two triglycosides, =0A                               =\n               Solasonine and Solamargine and their =0A                    =\n                          corresponding DI- and monoglycosides. =0A        =\n                                      Urea and salicylic acid are included =\n=0A                                              in the cream as keratolyti=\nc to enhance =0A                                              the penetrati=\non of BEC into the =0A                                              tumor a=\nnd to aid the removal of =0A                                              d=\nead tissues. It is intended for =0A                                        =\n      twice daily application to the lesion =0A                            =\n                  until complete eradication.</font></p>=0A                =\n                            <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font fac=\ne=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"3\"><b>History</b></font></p>=0A =\n                                           <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"story=\nbody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">As =0A        =\n                                      far back as 1825 it was reported =0A =\n                                             that extracts of the plant spe=\ncies =0A                                              Solanum were effectiv=\ne in treating =0A                                              cancers. It =\nhas now been established =0A                                              t=\nhat the anti-neoplastic compounds =0A                                      =\n        in these extracts were glycoalkaloids.</font></p>=0A               =\n                             <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font fa=\nce=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"> =0A                        =\n                      In the early eighties, an Australian =0A             =\n                                 biochemist, Dr. Bill Cham, observed =0A   =\n                                           that a number of cattlemen in th=\ne =0A                                              Brisbane, Queensland, ar=\nea were =0A                                              using the juice of=\n a naturally growing =0A                                              plant=\n called locally &#147; Devil =0A                                           =\n   &#146;s Apple &#148; (Solanum Sodomaeum) =0A                            =\n                  to cure cancer that had developed =0A                    =\n                          around the eyes of some of their =0A             =\n                                 cattle. Dr. Cham and his fellow =0A       =\n                                       scientists isolated Solasodine and =\n=0A                                              applied it to cancer cells=\n in a =0A                                              laboratory environme=\nnt. They looked =0A                                              at various=\n types of cancer including =0A                                             =\n ovarian, lung, breast and skin and =0A                                    =\n          the effects of Solasodine. The results =0A                       =\n                       were very encouraging in all areas, =0A             =\n                                 however as Australia has the highest =0A  =\n                                            incidence of Skin Cancer and so=\nlar =0A                                              Keratosis (pre-skin ca=\nncer) in the =0A                                              world, Dr. Ch=\nam elected to continue =0A                                              the=\n work in this area. After years =0A                                        =\n      of research, he developed a commercial =0A                           =\n                   product called Curaderm. Curaderm =0A                   =\n                           , was licensed as a Prescription =0A            =\n                                  Only Medicine for the treatment =0A      =\n                                        of actinic Keratosis by the Therape=\nutics =0A                                              Goods Administration=\n (TGA) in 1991 =0A                                              in Australi=\na.</font></p>=0A                                            <p align=3D\"lef=\nt\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"=\n3\"><b>Regulatory</b></font></p>=0A                                         =\n   <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sa=\nns-serif\" size=3D\"2\">In =0A                                              19=\n96 an application to have a pre-IND =0A                                    =\n          meeting with the United States Food =0A                          =\n                    and Drug Administration (FDA) was =0A                  =\n                            filed and allowed. At this meeting =0A         =\n                                     FDA informed that once the IND had =0A=\n                                              been granted this application=\n would =0A                                              be put in what FDA =\ncalls &#147; =0A                                              fast track &#=\n147;.                         =\n            and indicated that two extra arms =0A                          =\n                    would be required during the clinical =0A              =\n                                trial due to these two ingredients =0A     =\n                                         out of the product and by so doing =\n=0A                                              had to re-engineer the act=\nive ingredient, =0A                                              thereby cr=\neating a new product that =0A                                              =\nwe call BEC-5.</font></p>=0A                                            <p =\nalign=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-ser=\nif\" size=3D\"2\"> =0A size=3D\"3\">Skin =0A                                =\n              Cancer </font></b></font></p>=0A                             =\n               <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><font face=3D\"Arial, H=\nelvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">There =0A                                 =\n             are three primary types of skin =0A                           =\n                   cancer: Basal Cell Carcinoma (BCC), =0A                 =\n                             Squamous Cell Carcinoma (SCC) and =0A         =\n                                     Melanoma. BCC and SCC, the most =0A   =\n                                           common forms, are often grouped =\n=0A                                              as non-melanoma skin cance=\nr; they =0A                                              account for about =\none million new =0A                                              cases of s=\nkin cancer each year in =0A                                              th=\ne USA and approximately 800,000 =0A                                        =\n      new cases in the European Union. =0A                                 =\n             It is estimated that approximately =0A                        =\n                      40,000 people in the USA will develop =0A            =\n                                  melanoma this year, approximately =0A    =\n                                          this same amount applies to the =\n=0A                                              European Union. BCC is the=\n most =0A                                              common form of skin =\ncancer, affecting =0A                                              approxim=\nately 900,000 Americans =0A                                              ea=\nch year. One out of =0A                               =\n               every three new cancers is a skin =0A                       =\n                       cancer, and the vast majority is =0A                =\n                              Basal Cell Carcinoma. </font></p>=0A         =\n                                   <p align=3D\"left\" class=3D\"storybody\"><f=\nont face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\">Actinic =0A           =\n                                   Keratosis is a pre-cancer.                      over more traditional of conventional =\n=0A                                              methods of treatment of sk=\nin cancer:</font></p>=0A class=3D\"style5\">Coltan</span></strong>=\n<span class=3D\"style5\"> is the industrial name for columbite&ndash;tantalit=\ne, a dull black metallic mineral from which   the elements niobium (formerl=\ny   \"columbium\") and tantalum are   extracted. The niobium-dominant mineral=\n is columbite, hence the \"col\" half of   the term. The mineral concentrates=\n dominated by tantalum are referred to as tantalite.</span></p>=0A         =\n                             <ul>=0A                                       =\n <li><font </table>=\n=0A                                    </div>=0A                           =\n           <div align=3D\"center\">=0A                                       =\n <blockquote><strong>Properties:</strong> Tantalum is a heavy, hard gray me=\ntal. Pure tantalum is   ductile and may be drawn into very fine wire. Tanta=\nlum is practically immune to   chemical attack at temperatures lower than 1=\n50 &deg;C. It is only attacked by   hydrofluoric acid, acidic solutions of =\nthe fluoride ion, and free sulfur   trioxide. Alkalis attack tantalum very =\nslowly. At higher temperatures, tantalum   is more reactive. The melting po=\nint of tantalum is very high, exceeded only by   that of tungsten and rheni=\num. The melting point of tantalum is 2996 &deg;C; boiling   point is 5425 +=\n/- 100 &deg;C; specific gravity is 16.654; valence is usually 5, but   may =\nbe 2, 3, or 4.</blockquote>=0A                                  </div></td>=\n=0A                                </tr>=0A                              </=\ntable>=0A                              <h2>Genesis Group                   =\n
