<strong>The story begins=0A        =\n                                              in 1844, the struggle for=0A =\n                                                     independence in the Do=\nminican=0A                                                      Republic. L=\nead by the Great=0A                                                      Ge=\nneral Pedro Santana,=0A                                                    =\n  a leader of men, and the=0A                                              =\n        grower of the finest quality=0A                                    =\n                  tobacco in the Dominican=0A                              =\n                        Republic - frees the people=0A                     =\n                                 from the holds of Haiti.=0A               =\n                                       With their heritage's deeply=0A     =\n                                                 rooted in the Dominican=0A=\n                                                      Republic.<br>=0A     =\n                                                             <br>=0A       =\n Known for its old Spanish ruins, palm-lined beaches, tobacco, and Latin=0A=\n        lifestyle, the Dominican Republic is the second largest nation in t=\nhe=0A        Caribbean Sea. Although parts of the country have been develop=\ned for=0A        the tourist market, much remains untouched, unspoiled, and=\n virtually=0A        unvisited. The Dominican Republic offers the highest m=\nountain in the=0A        Caribbean, the authentic Spanish atmosphere of Old=\n Santo Domingo, the=0A        vast plains of sugarcane, white sand beaches,=\n and of course the finest=0A        tobaccos of the world<br>=0A           =\n     <br>=0A        Making the world's finest cigar is a life long goal of =\nthe Martinez Santana=0A        Cigar Company. Each cigar uses only the fine=\nst of specially blended and=0A        aged tobacco from the premier growing=\n region of the Dominican Republic.=0A        The tobacco is then wrapped in=\n a timely aged wrapper and skillfully hand=0A        rolled to produce a ci=\ngar that the Company calls its own.<br>=0A                <br>=0A        Ma=\nrtinez Santana takes great pride in introducing their own.</strong></p>=0A =\n                                     <font color=3D\"brown\"><a href=3D\"#Top\"=\n class=3D\"style7\">Top=0A                                      of Page</a> <=\n/font></td>=0A Rice contains two carbohydrate =0A              com=\nponents - amilopectin and amilose. The amount of amilose controls =0A      =\n        the firmness of the rice and runs an average of 22 % to 24 % in =0A=\n              Texas. A higher percentage of amilose leaves the rice firmer:=\n a =0A              lower percentage, as found in other rice growing areas,=\n leaves the =0A              rice softer. =\n                        <td colspan=3D\"2\" height=3D\"509\"><div align=3D\"left=\n\">=0A                                      <p align=3D\"center\"><font size=\n=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial Rounded MT 72,223,000 mill=\nion tons of Soybean in 1999=0A          and 75,378,000 million tons in 2000=\n. It is the single largest producer=0A          of soybeans in the world.<b=\nr>=0A          Within the United States, production is concentrated in thre=\ne main=0A          states, Iowa, Illinois and Minnesota. In 1999, Iowa prod=\nuced 502 million=0A          bushels, Illinois produced 469 million bushels=\n and Minnesota produced=0A          286 million bushels. <br>=0A          W=\nhen forecasting futures prices it is, therefore, essential to track=0A     =\n     local weather conditions, the local elevator price and planting and=0A=\n          harvesting progress in these areas. </font></p>=0A               =\n                       <p align=3D\"center\"><img src=3D\"../images/wr_sb_sbm_=\nproduction.gif\" width=3D\"350\" height=3D\"232\" border=3D\"1\"></p>=0A          =\n                            <p><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial Rounded MT Bo=\nld\"><img src=3D\"/genesis/images/spacer.gif\" width=3D\"10\" height=3D\"10\" alig=\nn=3D\"absmiddle\"></font><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"=\n3\"><br>=0A          World Trend in Soybean &amp; Soybean Meal Production</f=\nont><font face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\" size=3D\"2\"><br>=0A         =\n According to the United States Department of Agriculture statistics,=0A   =\n       global production of both soybeans &amp; soybean meal has been incre=\nasing=0A          steadily since 1996. In 1996, the soybean production occu=\npied 50.5=0A          per cent, or 132.22 million metric tons, of the world=\n's total oilseed=0A          output, which stood at 261.40 million metric t=\nons. In January 2001,=0A          the estimated figure for world's producti=\non of soybean reaches 167.18=0A          million metric tons, which occupie=\ns approximately 50.1 per cent of=0A          the global oilseed output at 3=\n03.47 million metric tons. Source: United=0A          States Department of =\nAgriculture (USDA)<br>=0A          One of the reasons behind this upward tr=\nend comes from the demand for=0A          soybean meal in animal feed. As g=\nlobal demand for meat consumption=0A          rises, the demand for animal =\nfeed also increases. Madagascar=0A            is intense enough for GCMG, whose extract has lo=\nng been the choice=0A            of bakers and ice cream makers. This vanil=\nla is known as &ldquo;bourbon=0A            vanilla.&rdquo; The=0A         =\n   term dates from the time when Madagascar and several other vanilla-growi=\nng=0A            islands were under French rule and were called the Bourbon=\n Islands.=0A            The vanilla beans are whole 6&quot;-7&rdquo; pods, =\neach equivalent=0A            to approximately 1 tablespoon of extract.</fo=\nnt></p>=0A          <table width=3D\"730\" border=3D\"0\" align=3D\"center\">=0A =\n           <tr>=0A              <td><div align=3D\"center\"><img src=3D\"image=\ns/VanillaRack.jpg\" width=3D\"320\" height=3D\"240\"></div></td>=0A             =\n <td><div align=3D\"center\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-=\nserif\"><img src=3D\"images/VanillaBundle.jpg\" width=3D\"320\" height=3D\"240\"><=\n/font></div></td>=0A            </tr>=0A          </table>=0A          <p a=\nlign=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><stron=\ng>Varieties: </strong><br>=0A            There are 110 varieties of vanilla=\n only two varieties are used commercially,=0A              Bourbon and =0A =\n         Tahitian. </font></p>=0A          <p><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Aria=\nl, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Bourbon vanilla: </strong><br>=0ABourbon =\nvanilla is the common name for Vanilla Planifolia. Vanilla Planifolia=0A   =\n originates from Mexico. Bourbon vanilla cuttings were taken from Mexico to=\n=0A    Reunion Island 1000 miles east of the coast of Africa in the 1800's =\nand grown=0A    by the French on large plantations. Reunion was then known =\nas the Ile de=0A    Bourbon from which this variety takes its name. </font>=\n</p>=0A          <p><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">=\n<strong>Tahitian vanilla: </strong><br>=0A            Tahitian vanilla is t=\nhe common name for Vanilla Tahitensis. This=0A              variety origina=\ntes from =0A            Bourbon plant stock taken to Tahiti, Vanilla Tahite=\nnsis mutated in=0A            the wild and now =0A            regarded as a=\n different species. Its appearance is smaller and its=0A            flavor =\nis=0A            considerably different than Bourbon vanilla. Tahitian vani=\nlla is=0A            sweet and fruity and =0A            contains less natu=\nral vanillin. It has a floral fragrance and the=0A            bean is fatte=\nr and =0A          moister than Bourbon vanilla. </font></p>=0A          <p=\n><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Bourbon vanilla has=\n the familiar vanilla flavor that we have come=0A              to savor in =\ndesserts =0A          and in ice cream. </font></p>=0A          <p><font si=\nze=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">Vanilla is one=0A           =\n   of the world's most labor intensive crops, second only to saffron. =0A  =\n          This explains why vanilla is so expensive. =0A          </font></=\np>=0A          <p><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><s=\ntrong>Processing:</strong> <br>=0A            Vanilla Beans are carefully p=\nicked at the peak of ripeness=0A             and are cured by the =0A      =\n      old Totonaca Natural Cycle by the sun. They are naturally sun sweat/c=\nured.=0A            No hot water=0A            or steam is used to accelera=\nte Nature's process. No chemicals are=0A            ever used. =0A         =\n Our Vanilla Beans are 100% Organically grown and cured. </font></p>=0A    =\n      <p>            <font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"=\n><strong>Storage: </strong><br>=0AVanilla Beans should NOT be refrigerated.=\n Store them sealed in a cool, dry, dark=0Aplace at ROOM TEMPERATURE . After=\n some time the beans may dry out. This is a normal change. =0AReconstitute =\nthem by soaking them in a liquid to be used in your recipe. </font> </p>=0A=\n          </div></td>=0A    </tr>=0A    <tr> =0A      <td><p align=3D\"left\"=\n>          <font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Product=\n=0A              Availability:</b> </font></p>=0A        <ul><p><font size=\n=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><strong>Grade=0A              =\n  1 </strong>: 7=0A          MT available<br>=0A          vanillin rate: 1.=\n7 minimum<br>=0A          Moisture rate : 22-24%=0A              <br>=0A   =\n           Price: US$Call / Kg CIF NY =0A              </font>=0A        <p=\n><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> <strong>Grade=0A  =\n            2</strong>&nbsp; :=0A            3 MT available<br>=0A         =\n vanillin rate: 1.6 min<br>=0A          Moisture=0A            Rate: 22-24%=\n<br>=0A            Price: US$Call / Kg CIF NY</font>=0A        <p><font siz=\ne=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\">=0A            <strong>CUTS</=\nstrong> : 5 MT available<br>=0A            vanillin rate: 0.9<br>=0A       =\n     Moisture Rate: 22=0A            -24%<br>=0A          Price: US$Call / =\nKg&nbsp;CIF NY </font></p>=0A        <p><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Hel=\nvetica, sans-serif\">The size of the=0A            Vanilla is 14-20+cm </fon=\nt><br>=0A            &nbsp;<br>=0A            <font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Aria=\nl, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Request for=0A                 Quote:</b> <a h=\nref=3D\"http://www.genesisny.net/Commodity/BOForm.html\" target=3D\"_blank\">Re=\nquest=0A                 For Quote Form </a><br>=0A            Buyers must =\npresent signed Letter Of Intent and Bank Confirmation=0A             Letter=\n to Genesis. </font> <font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"=\n><br>=0A            Please advise destination point for CFR FO basis. Some can be used in place of hard =0A               =\n red winter or hard red spring wheat for bread-making. These varieties =0A =\n               can be thought of as hard red wheat with their bran color re=\nmoved. =0A                Others can be used in place of high protein soft =\nwhite wheat in =0A                noodle and snack food products. These var=\nieties are most similar =0A                to soft white wheat but they hav=\ne a harder texture and produce =0A                chunky versus floury part=\nicles when crunched. Hard white wheat =0A                kernels have a gol=\nden color and lustrous appearance, like hard =0A                red winter =\nwheat, when cut open. Higher protein types can have =0A                a gl=\nassy internal appearance. </font> =0A              <p align=3D\"left\"> =0A  =\n          <li>=0A              <div align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D=\n\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Hard =0A                Red Winter Wheat<=\n/b> </font> </div>=0A              <p align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=\n=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> =0A                Hard red winter (HRW)=\n wheat is the dominant class in the United =0A                States in acr=\neage, production and use. HRW is used for bread, =0A                rolls a=\nnd, to a lesser extent, sweet goods and all-purpose flour. =0A             =\n   HRW wheat are intermediate in protein level with typical values =0A     =\n           between 12 and 13 percent. As the name states, HRW varieties hav=\ne =0A                a winter growth habit. HRW kernels are brick red in co=\nlor and =0A                have a lustrous appearance when cut open. Kernel=\n texture is hard =0A                and crushed kernels produce chunky part=\nicles. HRW kernels are =0A                typically larger than hard red sp=\nring wheat kernels. </font> =0A              <p align=3D\"left\"> =0A        =\n    <li>=0A              <div align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial=\n, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Hard =0A                Red Spring Wheat</b> </=\nfont> </div>=0A              <p align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Ari=\nal, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> =0A                Hard red spring (HRS) wheat =\nhas the highest protein level among =0A                the bread wheat It i=\ns the premier bread wheat. HRS is often used =0A                to fortify =\nhard red winter (HRW) flours for bread making. Bread-machine =0A           =\n     flours are generally made of a combination of HRS and HRW flours. =0A =\n               As the name states, HRS varieties have a spring growth habit=\n. =0A                High protein HRS kernels are brick red in color and ha=\nve a glassy =0A                appearance when cut open. HRS kernels tend t=\no be smaller than =0A                HRW kernels, have a deeper red color a=\nnd glassier texture. Kernel =0A                texture is hard and crushed =\nkernels produce chunky particles. =0A                </font>=0A          </=\nul>=0A        </div>=0A      </td>=0A    </tr>=0A    <tr bgcolor=3D\"#99CC99=\n\"> =0A      <td colspan=3D\"2\"> =0A        <div align=3D\"center\"></div>=0A  =\n      <div align=3D\"center\"></div>=0A      </td>=0A    </tr>=0A    <tr> =0A=\n      <td width=3D\"30%\" bgcolor=3D\"#CCCC99\"> =0A        <div align=3D\"cente=\nr\"><b><font size=3D\"4\">Soft Wheat</font></b></div>=0A      </td>=0A      <t=\nd width=3D\"70%\" bgcolor=3D\"#000000\"> =0A        <div align=3D\"center\"><img =\nborder=3D0 hspace=3D1 src=3D\"../../images/WheatS.gif\"><img border=3D0 hspac=\ne=3D1 src=3D\"../../images/closeupSW.gif\"> =0A        </div>=0A      </td>=\n=0A    </tr>=0A    <tr> =0A      <td height=3D\"459\" colspan=3D\"2\"> =0A     =\n   <div align=3D\"center\"></div>=0A        <div align=3D\"center\"> =0A       =\n   <ul>=0A            <li>=0A              <div align=3D\"left\"><font size=\n=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"><b>Soft =0A                Whi=\nte</b> </font> </div>=0A              <p align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" fa=\nce=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> =0A                Soft white (SW) whe=\nat is used to make flour for bakery products =0A                other than =\nbread such as cakes, crackers, cookies, pastries, quick =0A                =\nbreads, muffins, and snack foods. SW wheat tend to be low in protein =0A   =\n             (<10%) but higher protein levels (>11%) are desired for some p=\nroducts =0A                such as flat breads and noodles. There are both =\nwinter and spring =0A                varieties of SW wheat but unlike some =\nother market classes of =0A                wheat, no distinction is made be=\ntween the two. Low protein SW =0A                kernels are golden in colo=\nr and have a dull, chalky appearance =0A                when cut open. Kern=\nels have a soft texture and crushed kernels =0A                produce flou=\nry particles. Soft white wheat have a common wheat =0A                head =\ntype. Soft White Wheat Plant Info </font>=0A              <p align=3D\"left\"=\n><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif\"> =0A               =\n Soft white wheat is a grass-type plant. There are both winter =0A         =\n       and spring types. Winter types are typically planted in August =0A  =\n              through November. Spring types are typically planted in Janua=\nry =0A                through May. Grain is produced in structures called h=\neads or spikes. =0A                The heads tend to be oblong and may or m=\nay not have beards or =0A                awns on them. Soft white wheat ker=\nnels are oblong and tend to =0A                have a round profile. They t=\nend to be dull and opaque in appearance =0A                (they are not sh=\niny). </font> =0A              <p align=3D\"left\"> =0A            <li>=0A   =\n           <div align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetica, s=\nans-serif\"><b>Soft =0A                Red Winter Wheat</b> </font> </div>=\n=0A              <p align=3D\"left\"><font size=3D\"2\" face=3D\"Arial, Helvetic=\na, sans-serif\"> =0A                Soft red winter (SRW) wheat are similar =\nis use, protein content =0A                (<10%), and appearance to common=\n soft white wheat srw flours are =0A                typically used to produ=\nce flat breads, cakes, pastries, and crackers. =0A                Low prote=\nin srw kernels are orange-red in color and have a dull, =0A                =\nchalky appearance when cut open. Kernels have a soft texture and =0A       =\n         crushed kernels produce floury particles. srw varieties have a =0A=\n                winter growth habit and a common head type. The color diffe=\nrence =0A                between soft white and soft red wheat is due to a =\nsingle layer =0A                of colored cells in the bran layer of the k=\nernels.
